investigation:
Found by a fresh dogfooding parity sweep (2026-07-20). Minimal repro: `struct Acct { name: String }
fn main() {
  let mut m: Map[String, Acct] = Map.new();
  m.insert("a".to_string(), Acct { name: "alice".to_string() });
  let a = m.get("a").unwrap();
  print(a.name);
}` -> interp prints `alice`; `karac run` (JIT), `karac build` (AOT-O2) and `KARAC_OPT_LEVEL=0` (AOT-O0) all abort `free(): double free detected in tcache 2` (SIGABRT, exit 134). CONTROLS that WORK (isolating the trigger): (a) Map value = bare `String` (`Map[String,String].get().unwrap()`) — the FIXED B-2026-07-14-15 class, OK; (b) Map value = scalar-only struct (`struct Acct { txns: i64 }`) — OK; (c) `Vec[struct{String}].get(0).unwrap()` — the MAP double-free does not reproduce here, so the fix is Map-specific; NOTE the Vec accessor has its OWN separate latent bug filed as B-2026-07-20-9 (a FLAKY uninitialized/UAF field read — an earlier lucky run made this control read `alice` and was wrongly recorded as fully OK). Triggers regardless of key type (i64 or String) and with one or two struct fields (String / String+i64).

Found by a fresh dogfooding parity sweep (2026-07-20). Repro: `struct P { id: i64, w: i64 }
fn main() {
  let mut v: Vec[P] = Vec.new();
  v.push(P { id: 3, w: 30 }); v.push(P { id: 1, w: 10 }); v.push(P { id: 2, w: 20 });
  let s = v.sorted_by(|a, b| a.w.cmp(b.w));
  for p in s { print(f"{p.id},"); }
}` -> interp prints `1,2,3,`; `karac build`/`karac run` loud-bail `codegen failed: Vec/String method 'sorted_by' is not yet supported in codegen` (with the standard `--interp` hint). LOUD deferral, not a miscompile.

Found by the same fresh dogfooding sweep as B-2026-07-20-7 (2026-07-20), confirmed while fixing that one. Repro: `struct Acct { name: String }
fn main() {
  let mut v: Vec[Acct] = Vec.new();
  v.push(Acct { name: "alice".to_string() });
  let a = v.get(0).unwrap();
  print(a.name);
}`. `karac run --interp` always prints `alice`; `karac run` (JIT) and `karac build` (AOT) print `alice` on SOME runs and `0` on others — e.g. 8 successive JIT runs of a 2-element variant gave `alice,bob | 0,0 | 0,0 | alice,bob | 0,0 | 0,0 | 0,0 | 0,0`, and `.first().unwrap()` is equally flaky (`0 | alice | 0 | 0 | alice`). The nondeterminism across byte-identical runs is itself proof of a memory bug (uninitialized read or UAF), not a stable miscompile. It was masked at first discovery: B-2026-07-20-7's investigation recorded this control as fully OK because the single characterizing run happened to hit the `alice` outcome. A scalar-field struct element (`struct Acct { txns: i64 }`) and a bare `String`/`Vec` element are all fine — only a struct element WITH a heap field is affected.

enum Tok { Plus, Ident(String) }
struct SpTok { tok: Tok, n: i64 }
fn render(st: ref SpTok) -> String {
    match st.tok {
        Ident(name) => {
            return "id:".to_string() + name;
        }
        Plus => {
            return "+".to_string();
        }
    }
    return "?".to_string();
}
fn main() {
    let mut v: Vec[SpTok] = Vec.new();
    v.push(SpTok { tok: Tok.Ident("foo".to_string()), n: 1 });
    let t = v[0];
    println(render(t));
}

struct Span { line: i64, col: i64 }
enum Tok { Plus, Num(i64), Ident(String) }
struct SpTok { tok: Tok, span: Span }
fn mk(t: Tok, line: i64, col: i64) -> SpTok {
    return SpTok { tok: t, span: Span { line: line, col: col } };
}
fn render(st: ref SpTok) -> String {
    let mut head = "?".to_string();
    match st.tok {
        Ident(name) => {
            head = "id:".to_string() + name;
        }
        Num(n) => {
            head = "num:".to_string() + n.to_string();
        }
        Plus => {
            head = "+".to_string();
        }
    }
    return head;
}
fn main() {
    let a = mk(Tok.Ident("foo".to_string()), 1, 2);
    println(render(a));
}
